ce:section.ce:para:
Interleukin-33 (IL-33) is a novel member of IL-1 family, which also includes IL-1 and IL-18. It was first identified as a nuclear factor in high endothelial venules (
Baekkevold et al., 2003
) and later recognized as a specific extracellular ligand for ST2 (
Schmitz et al., 2005
) based on its β-trefoil structure at the carboxyl terminus, which is a conserved structure for IL-1 cytokines. In the cell nucleus, IL-33 may act as a transcriptional repressor with a DNA-binding domain (
Carriere et al., 2007; Moussion et al., 2008
), and it is known to regulate the transcription of nuclear factor-κBp65 (
Choi et al., 2012
). Similar to high-mobility group box 1 (HMGB1), known as damage-associated molecular patterns (DAMPs or alarmins), IL-33 is released from necrotic cells when tissue is injured (
Moussion et al., 2008; Cayrol and Girard, 2009; Haraldsen et al., 2009
).

ST2 has two major isoforms: the transmembrane ST2 (ST2 or ST2L) and the soluble ST2 (sST2) (
Iwahana et al., 1999
), and the latter is considered a decoy receptor for IL-33 (
Xu et al., 1998; Sanada et al., 2007; Haraldsen et al., 2009
). IL-33 exerts its biological activity by interacting with its heteromeric receptor composed of ST2 and the IL-1 receptor accessory protein (IL-1RAcp).

The cytokine IL-33 and its receptor ST2 have attracted considerable interest since their identification. Although a number of studies have shown that IL-33 is expressed by endothelial (
Baekkevold et al., 2003; Schmitz et al., 2005; Kuchler et al., 2008; Moussion et al., 2008
), epithelial (
Carriere et al., 2007
) and smooth muscle cells (
Chackerian et al., 2007; Pushparaj et al., 2009
), the expression and distribution of IL-33 and ST2 in the CNS are uncertain. IL-33 has been documented to be expressed in brain astrocytes, but not in cortical neurons or microglia (
Yasuoka et al., 2011
). Similarly, our immunochemical results showed that IL-33 is expressed in spinal astrocytes (data not shown), which participate in the central sensitization of pathological pain (
McMahon and Malcangio, 2009; Milligan and Watkins, 2009
). Furthermore, a recent study has shown that IL-33 is co-expressed with glial fibrillary acidic protein
+
(GFAP
+
) astrocytes and NeuN
+
neuron cells in the spinal cord. (
Jiang et al., 2012
). Similar to IL-33, expression of ST2 in the CNS is disputable. ST2 has been shown to be expressed in astrocytes, but not in microglia or neurons in the brain (
Andre et al., 2005
), whereas ST2 has been shown to be expressed in both astrocytes and microglia (
Yasuoka et al., 2011
) or neurons in murine spine (
Jiang et al., 2012
). And our preliminary results showed ST2 distributed in the astrocytes and neurons in the spinal cord in the normal mice (data not shown). These results are inconsistent, possibly due to the different CNS regions studied or the administration of drugs from different companies. And the expression of ST2 in the spinal cord as well as DRG needs to be further proved. However, it is clear that both IL-33 and ST2 are expressed in the CNS, which suggests the involvement of the IL-33/ST2 pathway in CNS pain modulation.

A previous study reported that IL-33 could induce inflammatory pain in the peripheral nervous system and mediate antigen-induced cutaneous and articular hypernociception in mice (
Verri et al., 2008
). Here, we used the formalin test, which is the classic model of acute inflammatory pain. The mechanisms behind the two phases are considered to be different: the first phase is thought to result from the activation of peripheral nociceptors, whereas the second phase is thought to reflect the development of inflammation and central sensitization. Moreover, two different spontaneous nociceptive responses, paw licking and paw lifting, were monitored and used as parameters of pain intensity, similar to many previous studies (
Donahue et al., 2001; Yi et al., 2011
). Paw lifting behavior is thought to represent the outcome of peripheral or spinal mechanisms related to the sensory component of pain, whereas paw licking behavior also has a supra-spinal component in addition to reflecting changes in the periphery and spinal cord (
Donahue et al., 2001; Yi et al., 2011
).

Interestingly, in the present study both subcutaneous and intrathecal injection of IL-33 potentiated the pain response to formalin in both phases, and ST2 antibody attenuated the pain response in both phases. This suggests that IL-33 receptors may be critical for modulating injury-induced hyperalgesia as well as acute nociception at the peripheral and spinal level. Similarly, it is well known that morphine, a μ-opioid receptor agonist, can act both pre- and post synaptically on the primary afferent and morphine is well known to have an antinociceptive effect on acute and tonic pain (
Yamamoto and Yaksh, 1992; Nishiyama, 2000
). However, the analgesic effect of anti-ST2 antibody on the two phases in the formalin test is not through its actions on the opioid receptor because the analgesic effect of anti-ST2 antibody is not affected by naloxone (data not shown). Additionally, it has been reported that intrathecal administration of an NMDA receptor antagonist and an AMPA receptor antagonist shows a statistically significant effect on both phases caused by formalin injection in the hind paw of mice (
Nishiyama, 2000; Yoon et al., 2005
). Whether the effect of IL-33 is mediated by the NMDA or the AMPA receptor still needs to be determined.

As far as we know, IL-33 combines with ST2 to activate downstream signaling pathways, such as nuclear factor-κB (NF-κB), mitogen-activated protein kinases (MAPKs) (
Schmitz et al., 2005; Palmer et al., 2009
), and Janus kinase 2 (JAK2) (
Funakoshi-Tago et al., 2011
). A previous report indicated that spinal extracellular-signal-regulated kinase (ERK) was phosphorylated within minutes after the subcutaneous injection of formalin into the hind paw (
Ji et al., 1999
). Inhibition of spinal ERK1/2 phosphorylation by MEK inhibitors before the formalin injection, or deletion of the gene expression of ERK2, could significantly reduce the nociceptive behaviors of the second phase (
Ji et al., 1999
). These results imply that the behavioral response in the second phase is related to the phosphorylation of ERK (
Ji et al., 1999; Otsubo et al., 2012
). Additionally, it has been reported that formalin injection markedly increases phosphorylation of p38 MAPK (
Li et al., 2012
), and we found that the formalin-induced pain behavior was inhibited by the P38 MAPK signaling inhibitor SB203580 (data not shown). In addition, the transcription factor NF-κB is also thought to play an essential role in inflammatory processes and pain, and decreased nociceptive behavior was observed in NF-κB
−/−
mice in a previous study (
Niederberger et al., 2007
). Therefore, IL-33 most likely mediates inflammatory pain through the activation of the NF-κB or MAPKs, and this is currently under investigation in our group.
